	<section class="grid align-center page-section">
			<div class="col-2_sm-2_xs-12">
				<h5>OVERVIEW</h5>
			</div>
			<div class="col-7_sm-9">
				<div class="title-headerline"> </div>
			</div>

		<div class="grid align-center">
			<div class="col-7_lg-8_sm-10_xs-12">
				<div class="page-paragraph_block">
					<p>The collection and analysis of sports data has been around for decades, measuring and interpreting the performances of both players and teams, in an attempt to quantify successes and failures. The creation and growth of organized esports over the past 20 years, however, has opened the doors to collect immense amounts of performance data that our traditional analysis methods and standards are ill-equipped to handle.</p>
					<p>This project is an attempt to <b>re-contextualize and improve the visual communication of esports data</b> and statistics from my current favorite esport, the Overwatch League (or OWL). As a highly complex and team-oriented game, understanding the data from matches can be confusing and misleading as player or team performance can be easily misunderstood depending on the match-up, the characters played, the map type, or the current popular playstyle (or meta). As a big fan of the league and a former high-ranked player of the game myself, I wanted to <b>explore how these complicated and detailed stats could be used to support analytical arguments</b> as well as practice my UI design skills and data visualization best practices on a web-app platform.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>


