	<section class="grid align-center page-section">
		<div class="col-2_sm-2_xs-12">
			<h5>RESEARCH</h5>
		</div>
		<div class="col-7_sm-9">
			<div class="title-headerline"> </div>
		</div>

		<div class="grid align-center">
			<div class="col-7_lg-8_sm-10_xs-12">
				<div class="page-paragraph_block">
					<p>I looked at similar websites across different esports titles such as <a href="https://na.op.gg/aram/aatrox/statistics" target="_blank">League of Legends</a>,<a href="https://www.hltv.org/stats" target="_blank">CS:GO</a>, and <a href="https://www.valorbuff.com/stats" target="_blank"> Valorant</a>, as well as traditional sports with sites such as <a href="https://www.espn.com/" target="_blank">ESPN</a>. These sites gave me a lot of insight and inspiration into different methods of organizing and balancing content that is technical or dense. In particular, <b>strong typographic hierarchy paired with either eye-catching data visualization</b> or icons were the most successful at providing easy-to-understand context to numbers or data points that would otherwise be difficult to quickly understand. These types of visual treatments helped <b>guide users through each statistic, while also making the layouts scannable and easy to navigate.</b></p>
					<p>I dived deep into exploring the data that was available to me on the league's website in their <b><a href="https://overwatchleague.com/en-us/statslab" target="_blank"> Stats Lab</a>, a series of Tableau views highlighting and presenting different parts of the data</b> collected from team performance metrics to player statistics. A few of these pages are simple data charts tying performance stats to specific heroes, players, maps and matches with filter options, while others are more complex, such as one that displays specific team composition matchups over certain time periods. These views, created by <a href="https://twitter.com/CaptainPlanetOW">Ben Trautman</a>, OWL’s in-house stat wizard, reveal the breadth and complexity of data involved. With more than 300 different statistics captured during live matches the views are <b>focused on supporting the production of the OWL broadcast</b>, and their analyst segments, rather than the average fan. This means the views don’t need very much context, as the analysts and hosts include that in the broadcast themselves, and are often used to simply compare two players or teams to support the storylines and narratives of the league. While the Stats Lab is successful in this use, <b>the overall presentation isn’t very useful, or easy to understand</b>, to most fans.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

