	<section class="grid align-center page-section">
		<div class="col-2_sm-2_xs-12">
			<h5>DESIGN</h5>
		</div>
		<div class="col-7_sm-9">
			<div class="title-headerline"> </div>
		</div>

		<div class="grid align-center">
			<div class="col-7_lg-8_sm-10_xs-12">
				<div class="page-paragraph_block">
					<p><b>The design process for this project mainly revolved around iteration</b>. As a personal project, and an opportunity to practice and refine some UI and data visualization skills, I felt comfortable fleshing out initial ideas to test and analyze successes and failures. I’ve embedded a figma file above to show some of the process. As seen on the homepage iterations, <b>many of my first attempts felt like long repetitive lists and tables full of data but lacking meaning and context</b>. Separating filtering options into different sections felt like the right decision at first, to suggest a hierarchy of choices, but after designing and testing it, it became clear that was incorrect, as filter options should be grouped and treated equally. This iterative approach applied to most design decisions, from color palette to button styling, allowing me to practice and learn, while evolving the overall design. </p>
					<p><b>Creating the data vis elements was tricky at first</b>, I took a lot of inspiration from similar sites, and worked through what types of improvements could be made to fit particular data sets as well as remain technically feasible. It was <b>important to recognize which types of data necessitated a visualization and which didn’t</b>. Percentages could be paired with a simple bar if needed, but other data points such as rankings compared to other players needed a different solution. Some stats didn’t need a visualization at all.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>


